South African Corn Climbs for Third Day, Tracking U.S. Benchmark

-- B y   M k h u l u l i   M a n c o t y w a
-- 
2011-02-11T10:33:59Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-11/south-african-corn-climbs-for-third-day-tracking-u-s-benchmark.html
Corn advanced for a third day in
 South Africa , the continent’s largest producer of the grain, as
prices rose in the U.S., which competes for African export
markets.  White corn for July delivery added 44 rand, or 2.6 percent,
to 1,722 rand ($235) a metric ton, taking its weekly advance to
8 percent on the  South African Futures Exchange  in Johannesburg.
Meal made from the grain is the country’s staple food.  Corn futures for March delivery rose as much as 0.5 percent
to $7.0175 a bushel in electronic trading on the Chicago Board
of Trade today, and were last up 0.3 percent at $7.005.  Yellow corn for July delivery gained 35 rand, or 2 percent,
to 1,769 rand a ton. The grain, used mainly as  animal feed  in  South Africa , climbed 5.2 percent during the week.  Wheat for March delivery dropped 14 rand, or 0.4 percent,
to 3,392 rand a ton.  The gains or losses for the most active contracts of the
following crops today were as follows. All prices are in rand
and the crops are sold in tons:  To contact the reporter on this story:
